{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017Ky3dUgc4xaTNVCMZPhUuf","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→import type { TestGenerationContext, CodebaseIntelligenceContext } from './types';\n     2→\n     3→export const TEST_SIGNATURE = `export async function test(page: Page, baseUrl: string, screenshotPath: string, stepLogger: any)`;\n     4→\n     5→export const MCP_SYSTEM_PROMPT = `You are an expert visual regression test engineer. Use Playwright MCP tools to EXPLORE pages and discover accurate selectors, then OUTPUT standard Playwright test code.\n     6→\n     7→MCP TOOLS: browser_navigate, browser_snapshot (accessibility tree + refs), browser_click, browser_type, browser_wait_for\n     8→\n     9→WORKFLOW: navigate → snapshot → interact with refs → snapshot to verify → identify reliable selectors → OUTPUT test code\n    10→\n    11→CRITICAL RULES:\n    12→- NEVER guess selectors — always verify via browser_snapshot first\n    13→- Element refs (e.g. \"ref=s2e5\") are for MCP exploration only, NOT for final test code\n    14→- Do NOT use browser_take_screenshot during exploration — screenshots go in the OUTPUT test code\n    15→\n    16→DYNAMIC ROUTES (e.g. /users/[id]):\n    17→Navigate to the parent list page first, snapshot to find links with real IDs, then navigate to the actual URL.\n    18→\n    19→CONSTRAINTS:\n    20→- Use baseUrl for navigation (no hardcoded URLs)\n    21→- Capture at least one screenshot using screenshotPath\n    22→- Export async function \"test\" with exact signature: ${TEST_SIGNATURE}\n    23→- Do NOT use \\`import\\` — \\`expect\\`, \\`page\\`, \\`baseUrl\\`, \\`screenshotPath\\`, \\`stepLogger\\` are provided by the runner\n    24→- expect matchers: toBe, toEqual, toBeTruthy, toBeFalsy, toContain, toHaveLength, toMatch, toMatchObject, toHaveURL, toHaveTitle, toBeVisible, toBeHidden, toHaveText, toContainText, toHaveAttribute, toHaveCount, toBeEnabled, toBeDisabled, toBeChecked, toHaveValue (all support .not)\n    25→- Never mix regex text and CSS selectors in one locator — use page.getByText(/pattern/i) for regex, page.locator('[attr=\"x\"]') for CSS\n    26→\n    27→FINAL OUTPUT: After exploration, generate standard Playwright test code using discovered selectors.\n    28→\n    29→\\`\\`\\`typescript\n    30→import { Page } from 'playwright';\n    31→\n    32→${TEST_SIGNATURE} {\n    33→  stepLogger.log('Navigating to page');\n    34→  await page.goto(\\`\\${baseUrl}/path\\`);\n    35→  await page.locator('[data-testid=\"discovered-element\"]').click();\n    36→  stepLogger.log('Taking screenshot');\n    37→  await page.screenshot({ path: screenshotPath, fullPage: true });\n    38→}\n    39→\\`\\`\\``;\n    40→\n    41→export const SYSTEM_PROMPT = `You generate Playwright visual regression tests. Output ONLY a JavaScript code block — NO explanations, NO analysis, NO text before or after the code.\n    42→\n    43→RULES:\n    44→- Plain JavaScript, NO TypeScript, NO imports\n    45→- Signature: export async function test(page, baseUrl, screenshotPath, stepLogger)\n    46→- Navigate: await page.goto(\\`\\${baseUrl}/path\\`, { waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded' })\n    47→- Wait: await page.waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded')\n    48→- URL assert: ALWAYS regex — await expect(page).toHaveURL(/\\\\/path/)\n    49→- Visibility: await expect(page.locator('body')).toBeVisible()\n    50→- Screenshot: await page.screenshot({ path: screenshotPath, fullPage: true })\n    51→- Log: stepLogger.log('message')\n    52→\n    53→AUTH: Tests run with pre-authenticated browser state (Playwright storageState).\n    54→- Do NOT add login steps — auth cookies are already set\n    55→- If redirected to /login or /sign-in, the auth state expired — take screenshot and return gracefully\n    56→- After page.goto(), optionally check: if (page.url().includes('/login')) { await page.screenshot({ path: screenshotPath }); return; }\n    57→\n    58→SYNTAX — CRITICAL:\n    59→- WRONG: const el: Locator = page.locator(...) → RIGHT: const el = page.locator(...)\n    60→- WRONG: import { expect } from '@playwright/test' → RIGHT: (no imports — expect is a parameter)\n    61→- WRONG: (page: Page, baseUrl: string) → RIGHT: (page, baseUrl, screenshotPath, stepLogger)\n    62→- Every statement must end with a semicolon or closing brace\n    63→- Every variable declaration must use const or let\n    64→- Verify all brackets/parens are balanced before outputting\n    65→\n    66→ASSERTIONS — prefer resilient checks:\n    67→- Use toContainText() over exact toHaveText() when possible\n    68→- NEVER use toBeTruthy() on textContent() or getAttribute() results — they return null when missing\n    69→- WRONG: const t = await el.textContent(); expect(t).toBeTruthy()\n    70→- RIGHT: await expect(el).toBeVisible() or await expect(el).toContainText(/expected/)\n    71→- Prefer toBeVisible() for element presence checks\n    72→- If checking a count, use toHaveCount() with the expected number\n    73→\n    74→EXAMPLE (static route):\n    75→\\`\\`\\`javascript\n    76→export async function test(page, baseUrl, screenshotPath, stepLogger) {\n    77→  stepLogger.log('Navigate');\n    78→  await page.goto(\\`\\${baseUrl}/settings\\`, { waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded' });\n    79→  await page.waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded');\n    80→  await expect(page).toHaveURL(/\\\\/settings/);\n    81→  await expect(page.locator('body')).toBeVisible();\n    82→  stepLogger.log('Screenshot');\n    83→  await page.screenshot({ path: screenshotPath, fullPage: true });\n    84→}\n    85→\\`\\`\\`\n    86→\n    87→EXAMPLE (dynamic route — discover real ID from list page):\n    88→\\`\\`\\`javascript\n    89→export async function test(page, baseUrl, screenshotPath, stepLogger) {\n    90→  stepLogger.log('Navigate to list page to find a real item');\n    91→  await page.goto(\\`\\${baseUrl}/tests\\`, { waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded' });\n    92→  await page.waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded');\n    93→  const firstLink = page.locator('a[href*=\"/tests/\"]').first();\n    94→  await expect(firstLink).toBeVisible();\n    95→  await expect(firstLink).toHaveAttribute('href', /\\\\/tests\\\\//);\n    96→  const href = await firstLink.getAttribute('href');\n    97→  stepLogger.log('Navigate to detail page: ' + href);\n    98→  await page.goto(\\`\\${baseUrl}\\${href}\\`, { waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded' });\n    99→  await page.waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded');\n   100→  await expect(page.locator('body')).toBeVisible();\n   101→  stepLogger.log('Screenshot');\n   102→  await page.screenshot({ path: screenshotPath, fullPage: true });\n   103→}\n   104→\\`\\`\\``;\n   105→\n   106→export function createTestPrompt(context: TestGenerationContext): string {\n   107→  const parts: string[] = [];\n   108→\n   109→  if (context.useMCP) {\n   110→    parts.push('Use MCP tools to explore the page, then generate standard Playwright test code.');\n   111→\n   112→    if (context.userPrompt) {\n   113→      parts.push(`\\nTest objective: ${context.userPrompt}`);\n   114→    }\n   115→\n   116→    if (context.targetUrl || context.routePath) {\n   117→      const route = context.targetUrl || context.routePath;\n   118→      parts.push(`\\nTarget: ${route}`);\n   119→\n   120→      if (context.isDynamicRoute) {\n   121→        parts.push(`\\nThis is a DYNAMIC route with parameters. You MUST:`);\n   122→        parts.push(`1. First browser_navigate to a parent/list page`);\n   123→        parts.push(`2. Use browser_snapshot to find links with actual IDs`);\n   124→        parts.push(`3. Navigate to discovered URL with real parameters`);\n   125→\n   126→        if (context.siblingRoutes?.length) {\n   127→          parts.push(`\\nRelated routes that may help find real data: ${context.siblingRoutes.join(', ')}`);\n   128→        }\n   129→      }\n   130→    }\n   131→\n   132→    // Add scan context if available\n   133→    if (context.scanContext) {\n   134→      parts.push(buildScanContextSection(context.scanContext));\n   135→    }\n   136→\n   137→    // Add codebase intelligence if available\n   138→    if (context.codebaseIntelligence) {\n   139→      parts.push(buildCodebaseIntelligenceSection(context.codebaseIntelligence));\n   140→    }\n   141→\n   142→    parts.push(`\\nWorkflow: navigate → snapshot → explore → OUTPUT Playwright test code with discovered selectors`);\n   143→    return parts.join('\\n');\n   144→  }\n   145→\n   146→  parts.push('Generate a Playwright visual regression test.');\n   147→\n   148→  if (context.userPrompt) {\n   149→    parts.push(`\\nTest objective: ${context.userPrompt}`);\n   150→  }\n   151→\n   152→  if (context.targetUrl || context.routePath) {\n   153→    const route = context.targetUrl || context.routePath;\n   154→    parts.push(`\\nTarget: ${route}`);\n   155→\n   156→    if (context.isDynamicRoute) {\n   157→      parts.push(`\\nIMPORTANT: This is a dynamic route. Before testing it directly:`);\n   158→      parts.push(`1. Navigate to the parent list page first (e.g., for /users/[id], go to /users)`);\n   159→      parts.push(`2. Wait for the list to load and find a valid link`);\n   160→      parts.push(`3. Click the link or extract the href to get a real ID`);\n   161→      parts.push(`4. Then test the actual page with real data`);\n   162→\n   163→      if (context.siblingRoutes?.length) {\n   164→        parts.push(`\\nRelated routes: ${context.siblingRoutes.join(', ')}`);\n   165→      }\n   166→    }\n   167→  }\n   168→\n   169→  // Add scan context if available\n   170→  if (context.scanContext) {\n   171→    parts.push(buildScanContextSection(context.scanContext));\n   172→  }\n   173→\n   174→  // Add codebase intelligence if available\n   175→  if (context.codebaseIntelligence) {\n   176→    parts.push(buildCodebaseIntelligenceSection(context.codebaseIntelligence));\n   177→  }\n   178→\n   179→  if (context.availableRoutes?.length) {\n   180→    parts.push(`\\n--- Available Routes (ONLY navigate to these) ---`);\n   181→    parts.push(context.availableRoutes.map(r => `- ${r}`).join('\\n'));\n   182→    parts.push(`\\nCRITICAL: Do NOT invent or guess URLs. ONLY use routes from the list above.`);\n   183→    parts.push(`If the test objective refers to a page not in this list, navigate to the closest matching route.`);\n   184→  }\n   185→\n   186→  // Add guidelines and requirements sections\n   187→  parts.push(`\n   188→--- Requirements ---\n   189→- Plain JavaScript only — NO TypeScript annotations, NO imports\n   190→- Signature: export async function test(page, baseUrl, screenshotPath, stepLogger)\n   191→- Navigate: await page.goto(\\`\\${baseUrl}/path\\`, { waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded' })\n   192→- URL checks: ALWAYS regex — await expect(page).toHaveURL(/\\\\/path/)\n   193→- Content checks: await expect(page.locator('body')).toBeVisible()\n   194→- Screenshot: await page.screenshot({ path: screenshotPath, fullPage: true })\n   195→- Log actions: stepLogger.log('message')\n   196→- Every variable MUST be declared with const or let\n   197→- Every statement must end with a semicolon or closing brace\n   198→\n   199→ASSERTIONS — CRITICAL:\n   200→- Prefer toBeVisible() for element checks, toContainText() for text\n   201→- NEVER use toBeTruthy() on textContent()/getAttribute() — they return null when missing\n   202→- WRONG: const text = await el.textContent(); expect(text).toBeTruthy()\n   203→- RIGHT: await expect(el).toBeVisible()\n   204→\n   205→BEFORE writing page.goto(), verify the URL is in the available routes list above.\n   206→\n   207→Return ONLY the code block, no explanations.`);\n   208→\n   209→  return parts.join('\\n');\n   210→}\n   211→\n   212→function buildScanContextSection(scanContext: import('./types').ScanContext): string {\n   213→  const lines: string[] = ['\\n--- Discovery Context ---'];\n   214→\n   215→  // Add source-specific context\n   216→  if (scanContext.discoverySource === 'nav-link' && scanContext.navLabel) {\n   217→    lines.push(`This route appears in navigation as \"${scanContext.navLabel}\".`);\n   218→    lines.push('Verify the page matches its navigation label purpose.');\n   219→  }\n   220→\n   221→  if (scanContext.discoverySource === 'spec-analysis' && scanContext.specDescription) {\n   222→    lines.push(`From specification: ${scanContext.specDescription}`);\n   223→    lines.push('Test the documented behavior.');\n   224→  }\n   225→\n   226→  if (scanContext.discoverySource === 'file-scan' && scanContext.sourceFilePath) {\n   227→    lines.push(`Source file: ${scanContext.sourceFilePath}`);\n   228→  }\n   229→\n   230→  // Add framework hint\n   231→  if (scanContext.framework) {\n   232→    lines.push(`Framework: ${scanContext.framework}`);\n   233→  }\n   234→\n   235→  // Add router type if relevant\n   236→  if (scanContext.routerType) {\n   237→    lines.push(`Router: ${scanContext.routerType}`);\n   238→  }\n   239→\n   240→  // Add test suggestions as scenarios to consider\n   241→  if (scanContext.testSuggestions && scanContext.testSuggestions.length > 0) {\n   242→    lines.push('\\nSuggested scenarios to consider:');\n   243→    for (const suggestion of scanContext.testSuggestions) {\n   244→      lines.push(`- ${suggestion}`);\n   245→    }\n   246→  }\n   247→\n   248→  // Add functional area context\n   249→  if (scanContext.functionalAreaName) {\n   250→    lines.push(`\\nFunctional area: ${scanContext.functionalAreaName}`);\n   251→    if (scanContext.functionalAreaDescription) {\n   252→      lines.push(`Context: ${scanContext.functionalAreaDescription}`);\n   253→    }\n   254→  }\n   255→\n   256→  return lines.join('\\n');\n   257→}\n   258→\n   259→function buildCodebaseIntelligenceSection(intel: CodebaseIntelligenceContext): string {\n   260→  const lines: string[] = ['\\n--- Project Intelligence ---'];\n   261→\n   262→  if (intel.framework) lines.push(`Framework: ${intel.framework}`);\n   263→  if (intel.cssFramework) lines.push(`CSS: ${intel.cssFramework}`);\n   264→  if (intel.selectorStrategy) lines.push(`Selector strategy: ${intel.selectorStrategy}`);\n   265→  if (intel.authMechanism && intel.authMechanism !== 'none detected') {\n   266→    lines.push(`Auth: ${intel.authMechanism} — protected routes may redirect to login`);\n   267→  }\n   268→  if (intel.stateManagement) lines.push(`State management: ${intel.stateManagement}`);\n   269→  if (intel.apiLayer) lines.push(`API layer: ${intel.apiLayer}`);\n   270→  if (intel.projectDescription) lines.push(`App: ${intel.projectDescription}`);\n   271→\n   272→  if (intel.testingRecommendations && intel.testingRecommendations.length > 0) {\n   273→    lines.push('\\nTesting recommendations:');\n   274→    for (const rec of intel.testingRecommendations.slice(0, 8)) {\n   275→      lines.push(`- ${rec}`);\n   276→    }\n   277→  }\n   278→\n   279→  return lines.join('\\n');\n   280→}\n   281→\n   282→export function createFixPrompt(context: TestGenerationContext): string {\n   283→  const parts: string[] = [`Fix this failing Playwright test. Return ONLY the complete fixed code in a code block — NO explanations, NO analysis, NO commentary.\n   284→\n   285→Original test code:\n   286→\\`\\`\\`typescript\n   287→${context.existingCode}\n   288→\\`\\`\\`\n   289→\n   290→Error message:\n   291→${context.errorMessage}`];\n   292→\n   293→  if (context.codebaseIntelligence) {\n   294→    parts.push(buildCodebaseIntelligenceSection(context.codebaseIntelligence));\n   295→  }\n   296→\n   297→  if (context.availableRoutes?.length) {\n   298→    parts.push(`\\nAvailable Routes (ONLY use these in page.goto()):`);\n   299→    parts.push(context.availableRoutes.map(r => `- ${r}`).join('\\n'));\n   300→    parts.push(`If the current page.goto() URL is not in this list, change it to the closest matching route.`);\n   301→  }\n   302→\n   303→  parts.push(`\n   304→ERROR DIAGNOSIS — identify the category FIRST, then apply the matching fix strategy:\n   305→- \"Unexpected identifier\" or \"Unexpected token\" → SYNTAX ERROR: Look for missing commas, semicolons, or unmatched brackets. Remove any TypeScript annotations (: Type, as Type). Remove any import statements.\n   306→- \"404\" or \"not found\" → WRONG URL: The page.goto() URL doesn't exist. Change it to a route from the available routes list.\n   307→- \"timeout\" or \"waiting for selector\" → SELECTOR MISMATCH: The element doesn't exist with that selector. Use broader selectors (getByRole, getByText) or remove the assertion.\n   308→- \"X is not a function\" → INVALID API: Using a non-existent method. Check expect() matcher names and Playwright API.\n   309→- \"Expected\" + \"Received\" → ASSERTION FAILURE: The page content doesn't match expectations. Loosen the assertion or use a more flexible match (toContain instead of toBe, regex instead of exact string).\n   310→- \"login\" or \"redirect\" or \"sign-in\" → AUTH ISSUE: Add auth state check — if (page.url().includes('/login')) return;\n   311→- \"net::ERR\" or \"ERR_CONNECTION\" → NETWORK ERROR: The server may not be ready. Add waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded').\n   312→\n   313→Instructions:\n   314→1. Identify which error category above matches the error message\n   315→2. Mentally trace the exact line that caused the error\n   316→3. Apply ONLY the minimal fix for that category — do not rewrite the entire test\n   317→4. Verify your fix actually changes something (not identical to input)\n   318→\n   319→COMMON FIX PATTERNS:\n   320→- \"Unexpected identifier\" often means a variable is used without declaration (missing const/let) or a line is missing a semicolon before the next statement\n   321→- \"Expected value to be truthy but got false\" means toBeTruthy() was called on a falsy value — replace with toBeVisible() on a locator, or remove the assertion entirely if it's not critical\n   322→- If you see \\`const x = await el.textContent(); expect(x).toBeTruthy()\\` → replace with \\`await expect(el).toBeVisible()\\` or \\`await expect(el).toContainText(/something/)\\`\n   323→\n   324→Rules:\n   325→- Write plain JavaScript only — NO TypeScript type annotations (no \": Page\", no \": string\", no \": any\")\n   326→- Do NOT use \\`import\\` — expect is provided by the runner\n   327→- ALWAYS use regex for URL checks: await expect(page).toHaveURL(/\\\\/path/); — never exact string URLs\n   328→- Never mix regex text and CSS selectors in one locator — use page.getByText(/pattern/i) for regex\n   329→- Every statement must end with a semicolon or closing brace\n   330→- Every variable declaration must use const or let\n   331→\n   332→DYNAMIC ROUTES: If testing a detail page (e.g., /tests/[id]), navigate to the list page first, find a real link, then follow it. Never hardcode fake IDs.\n   333→\n   334→BEFORE RETURNING — verify your output:\n   335→□ All page.goto() URLs match available routes listed above\n   336→□ No TypeScript annotations (: Type, as Type, <Type>)\n   337→□ No import statements\n   338→□ Every variable has const/let declaration\n   339→□ All brackets and parentheses are balanced\n   340→□ The fix addresses the specific error message above\n   341→□ Function signature is: export async function test(page, baseUrl, screenshotPath, stepLogger)\n   342→\n   343→Return ONLY the fixed code, no explanations.`);\n   344→\n   345→  return parts.join('\\n');\n   346→}\n   347→\n   348→export function createMcpFixPrompt(context: TestGenerationContext): string {\n   349→  const routeSection = context.availableRoutes?.length\n   350→    ? `\\nAvailable Routes (ONLY use these in page.goto()):\\n${context.availableRoutes.map(r => `- ${r}`).join('\\n')}\\n`\n   351→    : '';\n   352→\n   353→  return `Fix this failing Playwright test by exploring the live page with MCP tools. Return ONLY the complete fixed code in a code block — NO explanations.\n   354→\n   355→Original test code:\n   356→\\`\\`\\`typescript\n   357→${context.existingCode}\n   358→\\`\\`\\`\n   359→\n   360→Error message:\n   361→${context.errorMessage}\n   362→\n   363→Target URL: ${context.targetUrl || 'unknown'}\n   364→${routeSection}\n   365→ERROR DIAGNOSIS — identify the category FIRST:\n   366→- \"Unexpected identifier/token\" → SYNTAX ERROR: fix missing commas, remove TS annotations\n   367→- \"404/not found\" → WRONG URL: change to a route from available routes\n   368→- \"timeout/selector\" → SELECTOR MISMATCH: use browser_snapshot to find correct selectors\n   369→- \"Expected value to be truthy\" → replace toBeTruthy() with toBeVisible() on locator\n   370→\n   371→Instructions:\n   372→- browser_navigate to the target URL, then browser_snapshot to see current page structure\n   373→- Compare actual page selectors/content with the failing test to identify what changed\n   374→- Fix the test using discovered selectors; maintain the same function signature and intent\n   375→- Write plain JavaScript only — NO TypeScript type annotations, NO imports\n   376→- ALWAYS use regex for URL checks: await expect(page).toHaveURL(/\\\\/path/);\n   377→- Use only valid matchers (toBe, toEqual, toBeTruthy, toBeFalsy, toContain, toMatch, toHaveURL, toHaveTitle, toBeVisible, toHaveText, toContainText, toHaveAttribute, toHaveCount, etc.)\n   378→- Never mix regex text and CSS selectors in one locator — use page.getByText(/pattern/i) for regex\n   379→- If the error is \"Expected value to be truthy but got false\", replace toBeTruthy() with toBeVisible() on a locator or remove the assertion\n   380→- Every variable declaration must use const or let\n   381→- Every statement must end with a semicolon or closing brace\n   382→\n   383→BEFORE RETURNING — verify your output has no TypeScript, no imports, balanced brackets, and addresses the specific error.\n   384→\n   385→Return ONLY the fixed code, no explanations.`;\n   386→}\n   387→\n   388→export function createEnhancePrompt(context: TestGenerationContext): string {\n   389→  const parts: string[] = [];\n   390→\n   391→  parts.push(`Enhance this Playwright visual regression test:\n   392→\n   393→Current test code:\n   394→\\`\\`\\`typescript\n   395→${context.existingCode}\n   396→\\`\\`\\``);\n   397→\n   398→  if (context.userPrompt) {\n   399→    parts.push(`\\nEnhancement request: ${context.userPrompt}`);\n   400→  } else {\n   401→    parts.push(`\\nEnhancements to make:\n   402→- Add more assertions to verify page state\n   403→- Improve selector reliability\n   404→- Add checks for common edge cases\n   405→- Improve logging with stepLogger\n   406→- Add waits for dynamic content`);\n   407→  }\n   408→\n   409→  parts.push(`\\nReturn ONLY the enhanced code, no explanations.`);\n   410→\n   411→  return parts.join('\\n');\n   412→}\n   413→\n   414→export function createRouteScanPrompt(codebaseContext: string, repoFullName?: string, intelligence?: CodebaseIntelligenceContext): string {\n   415→  const repoLine = repoFullName ? `\\nRepository: ${repoFullName}\\n` : '';\n   416→  const intelSection = intelligence ? buildCodebaseIntelligenceSection(intelligence) : '';\n   417→  return `Analyze this codebase structure and identify all testable routes/pages.\n   418→${repoLine}${intelSection}\n   419→Codebase context:\n   420→${codebaseContext}\n   421→\n   422→Return a JSON object with a flat array of routes:\n   423→{\n   424→  \"routes\": [\n   425→    {\n   426→      \"path\": \"/users\",\n   427→      \"type\": \"static\",\n   428→      \"functionalArea\": \"User Management\",\n   429→      \"description\": \"User listing page\",\n   430→      \"testSuggestions\": [\"Verify user list loads\", \"Check pagination\"]\n   431→    },\n   432→    {\n   433→      \"path\": \"/users/[id]\",\n   434→      \"type\": \"dynamic\",\n   435→      \"functionalArea\": \"User Management\",\n   436→      \"description\": \"User profile page\",\n   437→      \"testSuggestions\": [\"Test with valid user ID\", \"Test error state for invalid ID\"]\n   438→    },\n   439→    {\n   440→      \"path\": \"/dashboard\",\n   441→      \"type\": \"static\",\n   442→      \"functionalArea\": \"Dashboard\",\n   443→      \"description\": \"Main dashboard page\",\n   444→      \"testSuggestions\": [\"Verify dashboard loads\", \"Check metric widgets\"]\n   445→    }\n   446→  ]\n   447→}\n   448→\n   449→Guidelines:\n   450→- Include all user-facing pages that benefit from visual regression testing\n   451→- Mark routes as \"static\" or \"dynamic\" based on URL parameters\n   452→- Use \"functionalArea\" to label the logical group (e.g. \"Authentication\", \"Settings\")\n   453→- Provide brief test suggestions for each route\n   454→\n   455→Return ONLY the JSON object, no explanations.`;\n   456→}\n   457→\n   458→export function createCodeDiffScanPrompt(\n   459→  changedFilesContext: string,\n   460→  baseBranch: string,\n   461→  headBranch: string,\n   462→  repoFullName?: string\n   463→): string {\n   464→  const repoNote = repoFullName ? `\\nRepository: ${repoFullName}` : '';\n   465→  return `You are analyzing code changes between two git branches to identify what visual regression tests should be created to cover the specific changes.\n   466→${repoNote}\n   467→Base branch: ${baseBranch}\n   468→Head branch: ${headBranch}\n   469→\n   470→Changed files and their contents:\n   471→${changedFilesContext}\n   472→\n   473→Analyze the actual code changes above and identify:\n   474→1. What specific functionality was added or modified\n   475→2. Which user-facing pages/routes are affected by these changes\n   476→3. What specific behaviors should be tested based on the diff\n   477→\n   478→For each affected route, generate test suggestions that target the EXACT changes — not generic page checks. For example:\n   479→- If a new button was added → \"Test the new [button name] button click behavior\"\n   480→- If form validation changed → \"Verify updated validation rules for [field]\"\n   481→- If a component was restyled → \"Check visual appearance of [component] after style changes\"\n   482→- If a new page was added → \"Test the new [page] route renders correctly with expected elements\"\n   483→\n   484→Return a JSON object with this exact structure:\n   485→{\n   486→  \"functionalAreas\": [\n   487→    {\n   488→      \"name\": \"Area Name\",\n   489→      \"description\": \"Brief description of what changed in this area\",\n   490→      \"routes\": [\n   491→        {\n   492→          \"path\": \"/affected-route\",\n   493→          \"type\": \"static\",\n   494→          \"description\": \"What changed on this page\",\n   495→          \"testSuggestions\": [\"Specific test targeting the actual code change\"]\n   496→        }\n   497→      ]\n   498→    }\n   499→  ]\n   500→}\n   501→\n   502→Guidelines:\n   503→- Group changes under logical functional areas based on what was modified\n   504→- Only include routes that are actually affected by the code changes\n   505→- Test suggestions MUST reference the specific change, not generic \"verify page loads\"\n   506→- Mark routes as \"static\" or \"dynamic\" based on URL parameters\n   507→- For dynamic routes, use bracket notation: /users/[id]\n   508→- If changes are purely backend/non-visual, still suggest routes where the effects would be visible\n   509→\n   510→Return ONLY the JSON object, no explanations or markdown formatting.`;\n   511→}\n   512→\n   513→export function createSpecAnalysisPrompt(specContent: string): string {\n   514→  return `Analyze the following specification/documentation content and extract functional areas, routes, and test scenarios.\n   515→\n   516→Specification content:\n   517→${specContent}\n   518→\n   519→Return a JSON object with this exact structure:\n   520→{\n   521→  \"functionalAreas\": [\n   522→    {\n   523→      \"name\": \"Area Name\",\n   524→      \"description\": \"Brief description of this functional area\",\n   525→      \"routes\": [\n   526→        {\n   527→          \"path\": \"/example-path\",\n   528→          \"type\": \"static\",\n   529→          \"description\": \"What this route does\"\n   530→        }\n   531→      ]\n   532→    }\n   533→  ],\n   534→  \"testScenarios\": [\n   535→    {\n   536→      \"route\": \"/example-path\",\n   537→      \"suggestions\": [\"Test scenario 1\", \"Test scenario 2\"]\n   538→    }\n   539→  ]\n   540→}\n   541→\n   542→Guidelines:\n   543→- Group related routes under logical functional areas\n   544→- Route type should be \"static\" or \"dynamic\" (dynamic routes have parameters like [id])\n   545→- For dynamic routes, use bracket notation: /users/[id]\n   546→- Test scenarios should be actionable visual regression test descriptions\n   547→- Focus on user-facing pages that benefit from visual testing\n   548→- Extract as many meaningful routes and test scenarios as possible from the spec\n   549→\n   550→Return ONLY the JSON object, no explanations or markdown formatting.`;\n   551→}\n   552→\n   553→export function createMCPExploreRoutesPrompt(baseURL: string, existingRoutes: string[], intelligence?: CodebaseIntelligenceContext): string {\n   554→  const seedSection = existingRoutes.length > 0\n   555→    ? `\\nAlready known routes (use as seed starting points to explore deeper):\\n${existingRoutes.map(r => `- ${r}`).join('\\n')}`\n   556→    : '';\n   557→  const intelSection = intelligence ? buildCodebaseIntelligenceSection(intelligence) : '';\n   558→\n   559→  return `You are exploring a live web application to discover all available routes/pages.\n   560→\n   561→Base URL: ${baseURL}\n   562→${seedSection}${intelSection}\n   563→\n   564→EXPLORATION INSTRUCTIONS:\n   565→1. Navigate to ${baseURL} and snapshot to find navigation links, sidebars, menus\n   566→2. Click through discovered links and record each unique URL pathname\n   567→3. Look for sub-navigation, tabs, or nested links on each page\n   568→4. Visit any known routes listed above as additional starting points\n   569→5. Note whether each route is static or dynamic (has IDs/slugs in the URL)\n   570→\n   571→IMPORTANT:\n   572→- Only record routes belonging to this application (same origin as baseURL)\n   573→- Convert dynamic segments to bracket notation (e.g., /users/123 → /users/[id])\n   574→- Do NOT include hash fragments, query parameters, or external links\n   575→\n   576→Return a flat JSON array of discovered routes:\n   577→\\`\\`\\`json\n   578→{\n   579→  \"routes\": [\n   580→    {\"path\": \"/dashboard\", \"type\": \"static\", \"functionalArea\": \"Dashboard\", \"description\": \"Main dashboard page\", \"testSuggestions\": [\"Verify dashboard loads correctly\", \"Check navigation elements\"]},\n   581→    {\"path\": \"/users/[id]\", \"type\": \"dynamic\", \"functionalArea\": \"User Management\", \"description\": \"User profile page\", \"testSuggestions\": [\"Test with valid user ID\", \"Test error state for invalid ID\"]}\n   582→  ]\n   583→}\n   584→\\`\\`\\`\n   585→\n   586→Use \"functionalArea\" to label the logical group for each route (e.g. \"Authentication\", \"Settings\").\n   587→\n   588→Return ONLY the JSON object inside a code block, no other text.`;\n   589→}\n   590→\n   591→export function createUserStoryExtractionPrompt(specContent: string): string {\n   592→  return `Analyze the following specification/requirements document and extract all User Stories (US) and their Acceptance Criteria (AC).\n   593→\n   594→Document content:\n   595→${specContent}\n   596→\n   597→Extract User Stories and Acceptance Criteria with the following rules:\n   598→1. Each distinct feature or capability should be its own User Story\n   599→2. Each User Story should have clear, testable Acceptance Criteria\n   600→3. Group related ACs under the same User Story\n   601→4. Provide a descriptive name for each AC that works as a test name\n   602→\n   603→Format your response as markdown using this exact structure:\n   604→\n   605→### User Story 1: [Functional area name]\n   606→**As a** [role]\n   607→**I want to** [feature/capability]\n   608→**So that** [benefit/value]\n   609→\n   610→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   611→- AC1: [Clear, testable criterion that describes expected behavior]\n   612→- AC2: [Another criterion]\n   613→\n   614→### User Story 2: [Next functional area]\n   615→...\n   616→\n   617→Guidelines:\n   618→- User Story titles should be concise functional area names (e.g., \"User Authentication\", \"Dashboard Analytics\")\n   619→- Each AC MUST describe a specific, observable user action and expected system response that can be verified in a browser\n   620→- Each AC should mention the specific page/route where the behavior occurs (e.g., \"On the /settings page, ...\")\n   621→- DO NOT include: questions, suggestions, meta-commentary, implementation tasks, or vague criteria\n   622→- DO NOT include ACs like \"Create additional tests...\", \"Consider...\", \"Should we...\", \"Implement...\", \"Ensure proper...\"\n   623→- Bad AC: \"Ensure proper error handling\" (vague, not testable)\n   624→- Good AC: \"When user submits login form with wrong password, an error message 'Invalid credentials' appears\"\n   625→- Bad AC: \"The system should display data correctly\" (vague, no specific elements)\n   626→- Good AC: \"On the /tests page, a table of tests is visible with columns for name, status, and last run date\"\n   627→- Each AC should be independently testable in a browser-based visual regression test\n   628→- Group ACs that test the SAME page/route under the same User Story\n   629→- If a requirement is not testable via browser interaction, skip it\n   630→- If the document doesn't follow formal US/AC format, infer them from the requirements`;\n   631→}\n   632→\n   633→export function createBranchAwareTestPrompt(context: {\n   634→  testName: string;\n   635→  acceptanceCriteria: string;\n   636→  userStoryTitle: string;\n   637→  userStoryDescription: string;\n   638→  targetUrl?: string;\n   639→  branchChanges?: {\n   640→    changedFiles: string[];\n   641→    fileDiffs?: string;\n   642→  };\n   643→  codebaseIntelligence?: CodebaseIntelligenceContext;\n   644→  availableRoutes?: string[];\n   645→}): string {\n   646→  const parts: string[] = [];\n   647→\n   648→  parts.push(`Generate a Playwright visual regression test for the following acceptance criterion.\n   649→\n   650→User Story: ${context.userStoryTitle}\n   651→${context.userStoryDescription}\n   652→\n   653→Acceptance Criterion: ${context.acceptanceCriteria}\n   654→Test Name: ${context.testName}`);\n   655→\n   656→  if (context.targetUrl) {\n   657→    parts.push(`\\nTarget URL: ${context.targetUrl}`);\n   658→  }\n   659→\n   660→  if (context.branchChanges) {\n   661→    parts.push(`\\n--- Branch Code Context ---`);\n   662→    parts.push(`The following files have been changed in the branch:`);\n   663→    for (const file of context.branchChanges.changedFiles) {\n   664→      parts.push(`- ${file}`);\n   665→    }\n   666→    if (context.branchChanges.fileDiffs) {\n   667→      parts.push(`\\nRelevant code changes:\\n${context.branchChanges.fileDiffs}`);\n   668→    }\n   669→    parts.push(`\\nUse this context to write more accurate selectors and assertions based on the actual code changes.`);\n   670→  }\n   671→\n   672→  if (context.codebaseIntelligence) {\n   673→    parts.push(buildCodebaseIntelligenceSection(context.codebaseIntelligence));\n   674→  }\n   675→\n   676→  if (context.availableRoutes?.length) {\n   677→    parts.push(`\\n--- Available Routes (ONLY navigate to these) ---`);\n   678→    parts.push(context.availableRoutes.map(r => `- ${r}`).join('\\n'));\n   679→    parts.push(`\\nCRITICAL: Do NOT invent or guess URLs. ONLY use routes from the list above.`);\n   680→    parts.push(`If the acceptance criterion refers to a page not in this list, navigate to the closest matching route and test what is available there.`);\n   681→  }\n   682→\n   683→  parts.push(`\n   684→--- Guidelines ---\n   685→- Write the test to verify the acceptance criterion\n   686→- Use descriptive stepLogger.log() messages matching the AC steps\n   687→- Add assertions that verify the expected behavior\n   688→- Capture screenshots at meaningful states\n   689→- Handle loading states for stable screenshots\n   690→\n   691→DYNAMIC ROUTES (paths with [id], [slug], etc.):\n   692→- First navigate to the parent list page (e.g., for /tests/[id], go to /tests)\n   693→- Wait for the page to load, then find a link or row in the list\n   694→- Click the first item or extract its href to get a real URL with an actual ID\n   695→- Then test the detail page with real data\n   696→- NEVER hardcode fake IDs like \"123\" or \"test-id\"\n   697→\n   698→SELECTORS (this app uses shadcn/ui + Tailwind CSS):\n   699→- Buttons: page.getByRole('button', { name: '...' })\n   700→- Inputs: page.getByRole('textbox') or page.getByLabel('...')\n   701→- Tabs: page.getByRole('tab', { name: '...' })\n   702→- Dialog: page.getByRole('dialog')\n   703→- Links: page.getByRole('link', { name: '...' })\n   704→- Headings: page.getByRole('heading', { name: '...' })\n   705→- Prefer getByRole/getByText/getByLabel over CSS selectors\n   706→\n   707→LOADING STATES:\n   708→- After navigation: await page.waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded')\n   709→- Before assertions: allow time for dynamic content to render\n   710→- For async data: await page.locator('[data-loading]').waitFor({ state: 'hidden', timeout: 5000 }).catch(() => {})\n   711→\n   712→--- Requirements ---\n   713→- Plain JavaScript only — NO TypeScript annotations, NO imports\n   714→- Function signature: export async function test(page, baseUrl, screenshotPath, stepLogger)\n   715→- Navigate: await page.goto(\\`\\${baseUrl}/path\\`, { waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded' })\n   716→- URL checks: ALWAYS regex — await expect(page).toHaveURL(/\\\\/path/)\n   717→- At least one screenshot must be captured\n   718→- Use baseUrl parameter for navigation\n   719→- Every variable MUST be declared with const or let\n   720→- Every statement must end with a semicolon or closing brace\n   721→\n   722→ASSERTIONS — CRITICAL:\n   723→- Prefer toBeVisible() for element checks, toContainText() for text, regex toHaveURL() for URLs\n   724→- NEVER use toBeTruthy() on textContent()/getAttribute()/innerText() — they return null when element is missing\n   725→- WRONG: const text = await el.textContent(); expect(text).toBeTruthy()\n   726→- RIGHT: await expect(el).toBeVisible() or await expect(el).toContainText(/expected/)\n   727→- WRONG: const href = await link.getAttribute('href'); expect(href).toBeTruthy()\n   728→- RIGHT: await expect(link).toHaveAttribute('href', /.*/)\n   729→\n   730→BEFORE writing page.goto(), verify the URL is in the available routes list above. If no route matches, use the closest parent route.\n   731→\n   732→Return ONLY the code block, no explanations.`);\n   733→\n   734→  return parts.join('\\n');\n   735→}\n   736→\n   737→export function extractCodeFromResponse(response: string): string {\n   738→  // Try to extract code from markdown code blocks\n   739→  const codeBlockMatch = response.match(/```(?:typescript|ts|javascript|js)?\\n([\\s\\S]*?)```/);\n   740→  if (codeBlockMatch) {\n   741→    return codeBlockMatch[1].trim();\n   742→  }\n   743→\n   744→  // If no code block, check if response starts with import or export\n   745→  if (response.trim().startsWith('import') || response.trim().startsWith('export')) {\n   746→    return response.trim();\n   747→  }\n   748→\n   749→  // Look for export async function anywhere in the response (AI may have added explanation before code)\n   750→  const funcMatch = response.match(/(export\\s+async\\s+function\\s+test\\s*\\([\\s\\S]*)/);\n   751→  if (funcMatch) {\n   752→    return funcMatch[1].trim();\n   753→  }\n   754→\n   755→  // Look for import statement followed by code anywhere in the response\n   756→  const importMatch = response.match(/(import\\s+[\\s\\S]*export\\s+async\\s+function[\\s\\S]*)/);\n   757→  if (importMatch) {\n   758→    return importMatch[1].trim();\n   759→  }\n   760→\n   761→  // Return as-is if we can't extract\n   762→  return response.trim();\n   763→}\n   764→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ec911d5a-d516-40b8-8771-7468f6b1ba97","uuid":"fe3c325a-d865-4874-9afb-996cb659903c","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/ewyct/dev/lastest2/src/lib/ai/prompts.ts","content":"import type { TestGenerationContext, CodebaseIntelligenceContext } from './types';\n\nexport const TEST_SIGNATURE = `export async function test(page: Page, baseUrl: string, screenshotPath: string, stepLogger: any)`;\n\nexport const MCP_SYSTEM_PROMPT = `You are an expert visual regression test engineer. Use Playwright MCP tools to EXPLORE pages and discover accurate selectors, then OUTPUT standard Playwright test code.\n\nMCP TOOLS: browser_navigate, browser_snapshot (accessibility tree + refs), browser_click, browser_type, browser_wait_for\n\nWORKFLOW: navigate → snapshot → interact with refs → snapshot to verify → identify reliable selectors → OUTPUT test code\n\nCRITICAL RULES:\n- NEVER guess selectors — always verify via browser_snapshot first\n- Element refs (e.g. \"ref=s2e5\") are for MCP exploration only, NOT for final test code\n- Do NOT use browser_take_screenshot during exploration — screenshots go in the OUTPUT test code\n\nDYNAMIC ROUTES (e.g. /users/[id]):\nNavigate to the parent list page first, snapshot to find links with real IDs, then navigate to the actual URL.\n\nCONSTRAINTS:\n- Use baseUrl for navigation (no hardcoded URLs)\n- Capture at least one screenshot using screenshotPath\n- Export async function \"test\" with exact signature: ${TEST_SIGNATURE}\n- Do NOT use \\`import\\` — \\`expect\\`, \\`page\\`, \\`baseUrl\\`, \\`screenshotPath\\`, \\`stepLogger\\` are provided by the runner\n- expect matchers: toBe, toEqual, toBeTruthy, toBeFalsy, toContain, toHaveLength, toMatch, toMatchObject, toHaveURL, toHaveTitle, toBeVisible, toBeHidden, toHaveText, toContainText, toHaveAttribute, toHaveCount, toBeEnabled, toBeDisabled, toBeChecked, toHaveValue (all support .not)\n- Never mix regex text and CSS selectors in one locator — use page.getByText(/pattern/i) for regex, page.locator('[attr=\"x\"]') for CSS\n\nFINAL OUTPUT: After exploration, generate standard Playwright test code using discovered selectors.\n\n\\`\\`\\`typescript\nimport { Page } from 'playwright';\n\n${TEST_SIGNATURE} {\n  stepLogger.log('Navigating to page');\n  await page.goto(\\`\\${baseUrl}/path\\`);\n  await page.locator('[data-testid=\"discovered-element\"]').click();\n  stepLogger.log('Taking screenshot');\n  await page.screenshot({ path: screenshotPath, fullPage: true });\n}\n\\`\\`\\``;\n\nexport const SYSTEM_PROMPT = `You generate Playwright visual regression tests. Output ONLY a JavaScript code block — NO explanations, NO analysis, NO text before or after the code.\n\nRULES:\n- Plain JavaScript, NO TypeScript, NO imports\n- Signature: export async function test(page, baseUrl, screenshotPath, stepLogger)\n- Navigate: await page.goto(\\`\\${baseUrl}/path\\`, { waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded' })\n- Wait: await page.waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded')\n- URL assert: ALWAYS regex — await expect(page).toHaveURL(/\\\\/path/)\n- Visibility: await expect(page.locator('body')).toBeVisible()\n- Screenshot: await page.screenshot({ path: screenshotPath, fullPage: true })\n- Log: stepLogger.log('message')\n\nAUTH: Tests run with pre-authenticated browser state (Playwright storageState).\n- Do NOT add login steps — auth cookies are already set\n- If redirected to /login or /sign-in, the auth state expired — take screenshot and return gracefully\n- After page.goto(), optionally check: if (page.url().includes('/login')) { await page.screenshot({ path: screenshotPath }); return; }\n\nSYNTAX — CRITICAL:\n- WRONG: const el: Locator = page.locator(...) → RIGHT: const el = page.locator(...)\n- WRONG: import { expect } from '@playwright/test' → RIGHT: (no imports — expect is a parameter)\n- WRONG: (page: Page, baseUrl: string) → RIGHT: (page, baseUrl, screenshotPath, stepLogger)\n- Every statement must end with a semicolon or closing brace\n- Every variable declaration must use const or let\n- Verify all brackets/parens are balanced before outputting\n\nASSERTIONS — prefer resilient checks:\n- Use toContainText() over exact toHaveText() when possible\n- NEVER use toBeTruthy() on textContent() or getAttribute() results — they return null when missing\n- WRONG: const t = await el.textContent(); expect(t).toBeTruthy()\n- RIGHT: await expect(el).toBeVisible() or await expect(el).toContainText(/expected/)\n- Prefer toBeVisible() for element presence checks\n- If checking a count, use toHaveCount() with the expected number\n\nEXAMPLE (static route):\n\\`\\`\\`javascript\nexport async function test(page, baseUrl, screenshotPath, stepLogger) {\n  stepLogger.log('Navigate');\n  await page.goto(\\`\\${baseUrl}/settings\\`, { waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded' });\n  await page.waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded');\n  await expect(page).toHaveURL(/\\\\/settings/);\n  await expect(page.locator('body')).toBeVisible();\n  stepLogger.log('Screenshot');\n  await page.screenshot({ path: screenshotPath, fullPage: true });\n}\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nEXAMPLE (dynamic route — discover real ID from list page):\n\\`\\`\\`javascript\nexport async function test(page, baseUrl, screenshotPath, stepLogger) {\n  stepLogger.log('Navigate to list page to find a real item');\n  await page.goto(\\`\\${baseUrl}/tests\\`, { waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded' });\n  await page.waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded');\n  const firstLink = page.locator('a[href*=\"/tests/\"]').first();\n  await expect(firstLink).toBeVisible();\n  await expect(firstLink).toHaveAttribute('href', /\\\\/tests\\\\//);\n  const href = await firstLink.getAttribute('href');\n  stepLogger.log('Navigate to detail page: ' + href);\n  await page.goto(\\`\\${baseUrl}\\${href}\\`, { waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded' });\n  await page.waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded');\n  await expect(page.locator('body')).toBeVisible();\n  stepLogger.log('Screenshot');\n  await page.screenshot({ path: screenshotPath, fullPage: true });\n}\n\\`\\`\\``;\n\nexport function createTestPrompt(context: TestGenerationContext): string {\n  const parts: string[] = [];\n\n  if (context.useMCP) {\n    parts.push('Use MCP tools to explore the page, then generate standard Playwright test code.');\n\n    if (context.userPrompt) {\n      parts.push(`\\nTest objective: ${context.userPrompt}`);\n    }\n\n    if (context.targetUrl || context.routePath) {\n      const route = context.targetUrl || context.routePath;\n      parts.push(`\\nTarget: ${route}`);\n\n      if (context.isDynamicRoute) {\n        parts.push(`\\nThis is a DYNAMIC route with parameters. You MUST:`);\n        parts.push(`1. First browser_navigate to a parent/list page`);\n        parts.push(`2. Use browser_snapshot to find links with actual IDs`);\n        parts.push(`3. Navigate to discovered URL with real parameters`);\n\n        if (context.siblingRoutes?.length) {\n          parts.push(`\\nRelated routes that may help find real data: ${context.siblingRoutes.join(', ')}`);\n        }\n      }\n    }\n\n    // Add scan context if available\n    if (context.scanContext) {\n      parts.push(buildScanContextSection(context.scanContext));\n    }\n\n    // Add codebase intelligence if available\n    if (context.codebaseIntelligence) {\n      parts.push(buildCodebaseIntelligenceSection(context.codebaseIntelligence));\n    }\n\n    parts.push(`\\nWorkflow: navigate → snapshot → explore → OUTPUT Playwright test code with discovered selectors`);\n    return parts.join('\\n');\n  }\n\n  parts.push('Generate a Playwright visual regression test.');\n\n  if (context.userPrompt) {\n    parts.push(`\\nTest objective: ${context.userPrompt}`);\n  }\n\n  if (context.targetUrl || context.routePath) {\n    const route = context.targetUrl || context.routePath;\n    parts.push(`\\nTarget: ${route}`);\n\n    if (context.isDynamicRoute) {\n      parts.push(`\\nIMPORTANT: This is a dynamic route. Before testing it directly:`);\n      parts.push(`1. Navigate to the parent list page first (e.g., for /users/[id], go to /users)`);\n      parts.push(`2. Wait for the list to load and find a valid link`);\n      parts.push(`3. Click the link or extract the href to get a real ID`);\n      parts.push(`4. Then test the actual page with real data`);\n\n      if (context.siblingRoutes?.length) {\n        parts.push(`\\nRelated routes: ${context.siblingRoutes.join(', ')}`);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Add scan context if available\n  if (context.scanContext) {\n    parts.push(buildScanContextSection(context.scanContext));\n  }\n\n  // Add codebase intelligence if available\n  if (context.codebaseIntelligence) {\n    parts.push(buildCodebaseIntelligenceSection(context.codebaseIntelligence));\n  }\n\n  if (context.availableRoutes?.length) {\n    parts.push(`\\n--- Available Routes (ONLY navigate to these) ---`);\n    parts.push(context.availableRoutes.map(r => `- ${r}`).join('\\n'));\n    parts.push(`\\nCRITICAL: Do NOT invent or guess URLs. ONLY use routes from the list above.`);\n    parts.push(`If the test objective refers to a page not in this list, navigate to the closest matching route.`);\n  }\n\n  // Add guidelines and requirements sections\n  parts.push(`\n--- Requirements ---\n- Plain JavaScript only — NO TypeScript annotations, NO imports\n- Signature: export async function test(page, baseUrl, screenshotPath, stepLogger)\n- Navigate: await page.goto(\\`\\${baseUrl}/path\\`, { waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded' })\n- URL checks: ALWAYS regex — await expect(page).toHaveURL(/\\\\/path/)\n- Content checks: await expect(page.locator('body')).toBeVisible()\n- Screenshot: await page.screenshot({ path: screenshotPath, fullPage: true })\n- Log actions: stepLogger.log('message')\n- Every variable MUST be declared with const or let\n- Every statement must end with a semicolon or closing brace\n\nASSERTIONS — CRITICAL:\n- Prefer toBeVisible() for element checks, toContainText() for text\n- NEVER use toBeTruthy() on textContent()/getAttribute() — they return null when missing\n- WRONG: const text = await el.textContent(); expect(text).toBeTruthy()\n- RIGHT: await expect(el).toBeVisible()\n\nBEFORE writing page.goto(), verify the URL is in the available routes list above.\n\nReturn ONLY the code block, no explanations.`);\n\n  return parts.join('\\n');\n}\n\nfunction buildScanContextSection(scanContext: import('./types').ScanContext): string {\n  const lines: string[] = ['\\n--- Discovery Context ---'];\n\n  // Add source-specific context\n  if (scanContext.discoverySource === 'nav-link' && scanContext.navLabel) {\n    lines.push(`This route appears in navigation as \"${scanContext.navLabel}\".`);\n    lines.push('Verify the page matches its navigation label purpose.');\n  }\n\n  if (scanContext.discoverySource === 'spec-analysis' && scanContext.specDescription) {\n    lines.push(`From specification: ${scanContext.specDescription}`);\n    lines.push('Test the documented behavior.');\n  }\n\n  if (scanContext.discoverySource === 'file-scan' && scanContext.sourceFilePath) {\n    lines.push(`Source file: ${scanContext.sourceFilePath}`);\n  }\n\n  // Add framework hint\n  if (scanContext.framework) {\n    lines.push(`Framework: ${scanContext.framework}`);\n  }\n\n  // Add router type if relevant\n  if (scanContext.routerType) {\n    lines.push(`Router: ${scanContext.routerType}`);\n  }\n\n  // Add test suggestions as scenarios to consider\n  if (scanContext.testSuggestions && scanContext.testSuggestions.length > 0) {\n    lines.push('\\nSuggested scenarios to consider:');\n    for (const suggestion of scanContext.testSuggestions) {\n      lines.push(`- ${suggestion}`);\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Add functional area context\n  if (scanContext.functionalAreaName) {\n    lines.push(`\\nFunctional area: ${scanContext.functionalAreaName}`);\n    if (scanContext.functionalAreaDescription) {\n      lines.push(`Context: ${scanContext.functionalAreaDescription}`);\n    }\n  }\n\n  return lines.join('\\n');\n}\n\nfunction buildCodebaseIntelligenceSection(intel: CodebaseIntelligenceContext): string {\n  const lines: string[] = ['\\n--- Project Intelligence ---'];\n\n  if (intel.framework) lines.push(`Framework: ${intel.framework}`);\n  if (intel.cssFramework) lines.push(`CSS: ${intel.cssFramework}`);\n  if (intel.selectorStrategy) lines.push(`Selector strategy: ${intel.selectorStrategy}`);\n  if (intel.authMechanism && intel.authMechanism !== 'none detected') {\n    lines.push(`Auth: ${intel.authMechanism} — protected routes may redirect to login`);\n  }\n  if (intel.stateManagement) lines.push(`State management: ${intel.stateManagement}`);\n  if (intel.apiLayer) lines.push(`API layer: ${intel.apiLayer}`);\n  if (intel.projectDescription) lines.push(`App: ${intel.projectDescription}`);\n\n  if (intel.testingRecommendations && intel.testingRecommendations.length > 0) {\n    lines.push('\\nTesting recommendations:');\n    for (const rec of intel.testingRecommendations.slice(0, 8)) {\n      lines.push(`- ${rec}`);\n    }\n  }\n\n  return lines.join('\\n');\n}\n\nexport function createFixPrompt(context: TestGenerationContext): string {\n  const parts: string[] = [`Fix this failing Playwright test. Return ONLY the complete fixed code in a code block — NO explanations, NO analysis, NO commentary.\n\nOriginal test code:\n\\`\\`\\`typescript\n${context.existingCode}\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nError message:\n${context.errorMessage}`];\n\n  if (context.codebaseIntelligence) {\n    parts.push(buildCodebaseIntelligenceSection(context.codebaseIntelligence));\n  }\n\n  if (context.availableRoutes?.length) {\n    parts.push(`\\nAvailable Routes (ONLY use these in page.goto()):`);\n    parts.push(context.availableRoutes.map(r => `- ${r}`).join('\\n'));\n    parts.push(`If the current page.goto() URL is not in this list, change it to the closest matching route.`);\n  }\n\n  parts.push(`\nERROR DIAGNOSIS — identify the category FIRST, then apply the matching fix strategy:\n- \"Unexpected identifier\" or \"Unexpected token\" → SYNTAX ERROR: Look for missing commas, semicolons, or unmatched brackets. Remove any TypeScript annotations (: Type, as Type). Remove any import statements.\n- \"404\" or \"not found\" → WRONG URL: The page.goto() URL doesn't exist. Change it to a route from the available routes list.\n- \"timeout\" or \"waiting for selector\" → SELECTOR MISMATCH: The element doesn't exist with that selector. Use broader selectors (getByRole, getByText) or remove the assertion.\n- \"X is not a function\" → INVALID API: Using a non-existent method. Check expect() matcher names and Playwright API.\n- \"Expected\" + \"Received\" → ASSERTION FAILURE: The page content doesn't match expectations. Loosen the assertion or use a more flexible match (toContain instead of toBe, regex instead of exact string).\n- \"login\" or \"redirect\" or \"sign-in\" → AUTH ISSUE: Add auth state check — if (page.url().includes('/login')) return;\n- \"net::ERR\" or \"ERR_CONNECTION\" → NETWORK ERROR: The server may not be ready. Add waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded').\n\nInstructions:\n1. Identify which error category above matches the error message\n2. Mentally trace the exact line that caused the error\n3. Apply ONLY the minimal fix for that category — do not rewrite the entire test\n4. Verify your fix actually changes something (not identical to input)\n\nCOMMON FIX PATTERNS:\n- \"Unexpected identifier\" often means a variable is used without declaration (missing const/let) or a line is missing a semicolon before the next statement\n- \"Expected value to be truthy but got false\" means toBeTruthy() was called on a falsy value — replace with toBeVisible() on a locator, or remove the assertion entirely if it's not critical\n- If you see \\`const x = await el.textContent(); expect(x).toBeTruthy()\\` → replace with \\`await expect(el).toBeVisible()\\` or \\`await expect(el).toContainText(/something/)\\`\n\nRules:\n- Write plain JavaScript only — NO TypeScript type annotations (no \": Page\", no \": string\", no \": any\")\n- Do NOT use \\`import\\` — expect is provided by the runner\n- ALWAYS use regex for URL checks: await expect(page).toHaveURL(/\\\\/path/); — never exact string URLs\n- Never mix regex text and CSS selectors in one locator — use page.getByText(/pattern/i) for regex\n- Every statement must end with a semicolon or closing brace\n- Every variable declaration must use const or let\n\nDYNAMIC ROUTES: If testing a detail page (e.g., /tests/[id]), navigate to the list page first, find a real link, then follow it. Never hardcode fake IDs.\n\nBEFORE RETURNING — verify your output:\n□ All page.goto() URLs match available routes listed above\n□ No TypeScript annotations (: Type, as Type, <Type>)\n□ No import statements\n□ Every variable has const/let declaration\n□ All brackets and parentheses are balanced\n□ The fix addresses the specific error message above\n□ Function signature is: export async function test(page, baseUrl, screenshotPath, stepLogger)\n\nReturn ONLY the fixed code, no explanations.`);\n\n  return parts.join('\\n');\n}\n\nexport function createMcpFixPrompt(context: TestGenerationContext): string {\n  const routeSection = context.availableRoutes?.length\n    ? `\\nAvailable Routes (ONLY use these in page.goto()):\\n${context.availableRoutes.map(r => `- ${r}`).join('\\n')}\\n`\n    : '';\n\n  return `Fix this failing Playwright test by exploring the live page with MCP tools. Return ONLY the complete fixed code in a code block — NO explanations.\n\nOriginal test code:\n\\`\\`\\`typescript\n${context.existingCode}\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nError message:\n${context.errorMessage}\n\nTarget URL: ${context.targetUrl || 'unknown'}\n${routeSection}\nERROR DIAGNOSIS — identify the category FIRST:\n- \"Unexpected identifier/token\" → SYNTAX ERROR: fix missing commas, remove TS annotations\n- \"404/not found\" → WRONG URL: change to a route from available routes\n- \"timeout/selector\" → SELECTOR MISMATCH: use browser_snapshot to find correct selectors\n- \"Expected value to be truthy\" → replace toBeTruthy() with toBeVisible() on locator\n\nInstructions:\n- browser_navigate to the target URL, then browser_snapshot to see current page structure\n- Compare actual page selectors/content with the failing test to identify what changed\n- Fix the test using discovered selectors; maintain the same function signature and intent\n- Write plain JavaScript only — NO TypeScript type annotations, NO imports\n- ALWAYS use regex for URL checks: await expect(page).toHaveURL(/\\\\/path/);\n- Use only valid matchers (toBe, toEqual, toBeTruthy, toBeFalsy, toContain, toMatch, toHaveURL, toHaveTitle, toBeVisible, toHaveText, toContainText, toHaveAttribute, toHaveCount, etc.)\n- Never mix regex text and CSS selectors in one locator — use page.getByText(/pattern/i) for regex\n- If the error is \"Expected value to be truthy but got false\", replace toBeTruthy() with toBeVisible() on a locator or remove the assertion\n- Every variable declaration must use const or let\n- Every statement must end with a semicolon or closing brace\n\nBEFORE RETURNING — verify your output has no TypeScript, no imports, balanced brackets, and addresses the specific error.\n\nReturn ONLY the fixed code, no explanations.`;\n}\n\nexport function createEnhancePrompt(context: TestGenerationContext): string {\n  const parts: string[] = [];\n\n  parts.push(`Enhance this Playwright visual regression test:\n\nCurrent test code:\n\\`\\`\\`typescript\n${context.existingCode}\n\\`\\`\\``);\n\n  if (context.userPrompt) {\n    parts.push(`\\nEnhancement request: ${context.userPrompt}`);\n  } else {\n    parts.push(`\\nEnhancements to make:\n- Add more assertions to verify page state\n- Improve selector reliability\n- Add checks for common edge cases\n- Improve logging with stepLogger\n- Add waits for dynamic content`);\n  }\n\n  parts.push(`\\nReturn ONLY the enhanced code, no explanations.`);\n\n  return parts.join('\\n');\n}\n\nexport function createRouteScanPrompt(codebaseContext: string, repoFullName?: string, intelligence?: CodebaseIntelligenceContext): string {\n  const repoLine = repoFullName ? `\\nRepository: ${repoFullName}\\n` : '';\n  const intelSection = intelligence ? buildCodebaseIntelligenceSection(intelligence) : '';\n  return `Analyze this codebase structure and identify all testable routes/pages.\n${repoLine}${intelSection}\nCodebase context:\n${codebaseContext}\n\nReturn a JSON object with a flat array of routes:\n{\n  \"routes\": [\n    {\n      \"path\": \"/users\",\n      \"type\": \"static\",\n      \"functionalArea\": \"User Management\",\n      \"description\": \"User listing page\",\n      \"testSuggestions\": [\"Verify user list loads\", \"Check pagination\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"/users/[id]\",\n      \"type\": \"dynamic\",\n      \"functionalArea\": \"User Management\",\n      \"description\": \"User profile page\",\n      \"testSuggestions\": [\"Test with valid user ID\", \"Test error state for invalid ID\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"/dashboard\",\n      \"type\": \"static\",\n      \"functionalArea\": \"Dashboard\",\n      \"description\": \"Main dashboard page\",\n      \"testSuggestions\": [\"Verify dashboard loads\", \"Check metric widgets\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n\nGuidelines:\n- Include all user-facing pages that benefit from visual regression testing\n- Mark routes as \"static\" or \"dynamic\" based on URL parameters\n- Use \"functionalArea\" to label the logical group (e.g. \"Authentication\", \"Settings\")\n- Provide brief test suggestions for each route\n\nReturn ONLY the JSON object, no explanations.`;\n}\n\nexport function createCodeDiffScanPrompt(\n  changedFilesContext: string,\n  baseBranch: string,\n  headBranch: string,\n  repoFullName?: string\n): string {\n  const repoNote = repoFullName ? `\\nRepository: ${repoFullName}` : '';\n  return `You are analyzing code changes between two git branches to identify what visual regression tests should be created to cover the specific changes.\n${repoNote}\nBase branch: ${baseBranch}\nHead branch: ${headBranch}\n\nChanged files and their contents:\n${changedFilesContext}\n\nAnalyze the actual code changes above and identify:\n1. What specific functionality was added or modified\n2. Which user-facing pages/routes are affected by these changes\n3. What specific behaviors should be tested based on the diff\n\nFor each affected route, generate test suggestions that target the EXACT changes — not generic page checks. For example:\n- If a new button was added → \"Test the new [button name] button click behavior\"\n- If form validation changed → \"Verify updated validation rules for [field]\"\n- If a component was restyled → \"Check visual appearance of [component] after style changes\"\n- If a new page was added → \"Test the new [page] route renders correctly with expected elements\"\n\nReturn a JSON object with this exact structure:\n{\n  \"functionalAreas\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"Area Name\",\n      \"description\": \"Brief description of what changed in this area\",\n      \"routes\": [\n        {\n          \"path\": \"/affected-route\",\n          \"type\": \"static\",\n          \"description\": \"What changed on this page\",\n          \"testSuggestions\": [\"Specific test targeting the actual code change\"]\n        }\n      ]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n\nGuidelines:\n- Group changes under logical functional areas based on what was modified\n- Only include routes that are actually affected by the code changes\n- Test suggestions MUST reference the specific change, not generic \"verify page loads\"\n- Mark routes as \"static\" or \"dynamic\" based on URL parameters\n- For dynamic routes, use bracket notation: /users/[id]\n- If changes are purely backend/non-visual, still suggest routes where the effects would be visible\n\nReturn ONLY the JSON object, no explanations or markdown formatting.`;\n}\n\nexport function createSpecAnalysisPrompt(specContent: string): string {\n  return `Analyze the following specification/documentation content and extract functional areas, routes, and test scenarios.\n\nSpecification content:\n${specContent}\n\nReturn a JSON object with this exact structure:\n{\n  \"functionalAreas\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"Area Name\",\n      \"description\": \"Brief description of this functional area\",\n      \"routes\": [\n        {\n          \"path\": \"/example-path\",\n          \"type\": \"static\",\n          \"description\": \"What this route does\"\n        }\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"testScenarios\": [\n    {\n      \"route\": \"/example-path\",\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Test scenario 1\", \"Test scenario 2\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n\nGuidelines:\n- Group related routes under logical functional areas\n- Route type should be \"static\" or \"dynamic\" (dynamic routes have parameters like [id])\n- For dynamic routes, use bracket notation: /users/[id]\n- Test scenarios should be actionable visual regression test descriptions\n- Focus on user-facing pages that benefit from visual testing\n- Extract as many meaningful routes and test scenarios as possible from the spec\n\nReturn ONLY the JSON object, no explanations or markdown formatting.`;\n}\n\nexport function createMCPExploreRoutesPrompt(baseURL: string, existingRoutes: string[], intelligence?: CodebaseIntelligenceContext): string {\n  const seedSection = existingRoutes.length > 0\n    ? `\\nAlready known routes (use as seed starting points to explore deeper):\\n${existingRoutes.map(r => `- ${r}`).join('\\n')}`\n    : '';\n  const intelSection = intelligence ? buildCodebaseIntelligenceSection(intelligence) : '';\n\n  return `You are exploring a live web application to discover all available routes/pages.\n\nBase URL: ${baseURL}\n${seedSection}${intelSection}\n\nEXPLORATION INSTRUCTIONS:\n1. Navigate to ${baseURL} and snapshot to find navigation links, sidebars, menus\n2. Click through discovered links and record each unique URL pathname\n3. Look for sub-navigation, tabs, or nested links on each page\n4. Visit any known routes listed above as additional starting points\n5. Note whether each route is static or dynamic (has IDs/slugs in the URL)\n\nIMPORTANT:\n- Only record routes belonging to this application (same origin as baseURL)\n- Convert dynamic segments to bracket notation (e.g., /users/123 → /users/[id])\n- Do NOT include hash fragments, query parameters, or external links\n\nReturn a flat JSON array of discovered routes:\n\\`\\`\\`json\n{\n  \"routes\": [\n    {\"path\": \"/dashboard\", \"type\": \"static\", \"functionalArea\": \"Dashboard\", \"description\": \"Main dashboard page\", \"testSuggestions\": [\"Verify dashboard loads correctly\", \"Check navigation elements\"]},\n    {\"path\": \"/users/[id]\", \"type\": \"dynamic\", \"functionalArea\": \"User Management\", \"description\": \"User profile page\", \"testSuggestions\": [\"Test with valid user ID\", \"Test error state for invalid ID\"]}\n  ]\n}\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nUse \"functionalArea\" to label the logical group for each route (e.g. \"Authentication\", \"Settings\").\n\nReturn ONLY the JSON object inside a code block, no other text.`;\n}\n\nexport function createUserStoryExtractionPrompt(specContent: string): string {\n  return `Analyze the following specification/requirements document and extract all User Stories (US) and their Acceptance Criteria (AC).\n\nDocument content:\n${specContent}\n\nExtract User Stories and Acceptance Criteria with the following rules:\n1. Each distinct feature or capability should be its own User Story\n2. Each User Story should have clear, testable Acceptance Criteria\n3. Group related ACs under the same User Story\n4. Provide a descriptive name for each AC that works as a test name\n\nFormat your response as markdown using this exact structure:\n\n### User Story 1: [Functional area name]\n**As a** [role]\n**I want to** [feature/capability]\n**So that** [benefit/value]\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- AC1: [Clear, testable criterion that describes expected behavior]\n- AC2: [Another criterion]\n\n### User Story 2: [Next functional area]\n...\n\nGuidelines:\n- User Story titles should be concise functional area names (e.g., \"User Authentication\", \"Dashboard Analytics\")\n- Each AC MUST describe a specific, observable user action and expected system response that can be verified in a browser\n- Each AC should mention the specific page/route where the behavior occurs (e.g., \"On the /settings page, ...\")\n- DO NOT include: questions, suggestions, meta-commentary, implementation tasks, or vague criteria\n- DO NOT include ACs like \"Create additional tests...\", \"Consider...\", \"Should we...\", \"Implement...\", \"Ensure proper...\"\n- Bad AC: \"Ensure proper error handling\" (vague, not testable)\n- Good AC: \"When user submits login form with wrong password, an error message 'Invalid credentials' appears\"\n- Bad AC: \"The system should display data correctly\" (vague, no specific elements)\n- Good AC: \"On the /tests page, a table of tests is visible with columns for name, status, and last run date\"\n- Each AC should be independently testable in a browser-based visual regression test\n- Group ACs that test the SAME page/route under the same User Story\n- If a requirement is not testable via browser interaction, skip it\n- If the document doesn't follow formal US/AC format, infer them from the requirements`;\n}\n\nexport function createBranchAwareTestPrompt(context: {\n  testName: string;\n  acceptanceCriteria: string;\n  userStoryTitle: string;\n  userStoryDescription: string;\n  targetUrl?: string;\n  branchChanges?: {\n    changedFiles: string[];\n    fileDiffs?: string;\n  };\n  codebaseIntelligence?: CodebaseIntelligenceContext;\n  availableRoutes?: string[];\n}): string {\n  const parts: string[] = [];\n\n  parts.push(`Generate a Playwright visual regression test for the following acceptance criterion.\n\nUser Story: ${context.userStoryTitle}\n${context.userStoryDescription}\n\nAcceptance Criterion: ${context.acceptanceCriteria}\nTest Name: ${context.testName}`);\n\n  if (context.targetUrl) {\n    parts.push(`\\nTarget URL: ${context.targetUrl}`);\n  }\n\n  if (context.branchChanges) {\n    parts.push(`\\n--- Branch Code Context ---`);\n    parts.push(`The following files have been changed in the branch:`);\n    for (const file of context.branchChanges.changedFiles) {\n      parts.push(`- ${file}`);\n    }\n    if (context.branchChanges.fileDiffs) {\n      parts.push(`\\nRelevant code changes:\\n${context.branchChanges.fileDiffs}`);\n    }\n    parts.push(`\\nUse this context to write more accurate selectors and assertions based on the actual code changes.`);\n  }\n\n  if (context.codebaseIntelligence) {\n    parts.push(buildCodebaseIntelligenceSection(context.codebaseIntelligence));\n  }\n\n  if (context.availableRoutes?.length) {\n    parts.push(`\\n--- Available Routes (ONLY navigate to these) ---`);\n    parts.push(context.availableRoutes.map(r => `- ${r}`).join('\\n'));\n    parts.push(`\\nCRITICAL: Do NOT invent or guess URLs. ONLY use routes from the list above.`);\n    parts.push(`If the acceptance criterion refers to a page not in this list, navigate to the closest matching route and test what is available there.`);\n  }\n\n  parts.push(`\n--- Guidelines ---\n- Write the test to verify the acceptance criterion\n- Use descriptive stepLogger.log() messages matching the AC steps\n- Add assertions that verify the expected behavior\n- Capture screenshots at meaningful states\n- Handle loading states for stable screenshots\n\nDYNAMIC ROUTES (paths with [id], [slug], etc.):\n- First navigate to the parent list page (e.g., for /tests/[id], go to /tests)\n- Wait for the page to load, then find a link or row in the list\n- Click the first item or extract its href to get a real URL with an actual ID\n- Then test the detail page with real data\n- NEVER hardcode fake IDs like \"123\" or \"test-id\"\n\nSELECTORS (this app uses shadcn/ui + Tailwind CSS):\n- Buttons: page.getByRole('button', { name: '...' })\n- Inputs: page.getByRole('textbox') or page.getByLabel('...')\n- Tabs: page.getByRole('tab', { name: '...' })\n- Dialog: page.getByRole('dialog')\n- Links: page.getByRole('link', { name: '...' })\n- Headings: page.getByRole('heading', { name: '...' })\n- Prefer getByRole/getByText/getByLabel over CSS selectors\n\nLOADING STATES:\n- After navigation: await page.waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded')\n- Before assertions: allow time for dynamic content to render\n- For async data: await page.locator('[data-loading]').waitFor({ state: 'hidden', timeout: 5000 }).catch(() => {})\n\n--- Requirements ---\n- Plain JavaScript only — NO TypeScript annotations, NO imports\n- Function signature: export async function test(page, baseUrl, screenshotPath, stepLogger)\n- Navigate: await page.goto(\\`\\${baseUrl}/path\\`, { waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded' })\n- URL checks: ALWAYS regex — await expect(page).toHaveURL(/\\\\/path/)\n- At least one screenshot must be captured\n- Use baseUrl parameter for navigation\n- Every variable MUST be declared with const or let\n- Every statement must end with a semicolon or closing brace\n\nASSERTIONS — CRITICAL:\n- Prefer toBeVisible() for element checks, toContainText() for text, regex toHaveURL() for URLs\n- NEVER use toBeTruthy() on textContent()/getAttribute()/innerText() — they return null when element is missing\n- WRONG: const text = await el.textContent(); expect(text).toBeTruthy()\n- RIGHT: await expect(el).toBeVisible() or await expect(el).toContainText(/expected/)\n- WRONG: const href = await link.getAttribute('href'); expect(href).toBeTruthy()\n- RIGHT: await expect(link).toHaveAttribute('href', /.*/)\n\nBEFORE writing page.goto(), verify the URL is in the available routes list above. If no route matches, use the closest parent route.\n\nReturn ONLY the code block, no explanations.`);\n\n  return parts.join('\\n');\n}\n\nexport function extractCodeFromResponse(response: string): string {\n  // Try to extract code from markdown code blocks\n  const codeBlockMatch = response.match(/```(?:typescript|ts|javascript|js)?\\n([\\s\\S]*?)```/);\n  if (codeBlockMatch) {\n    return codeBlockMatch[1].trim();\n  }\n\n  // If no code block, check if response starts with import or export\n  if (response.trim().startsWith('import') || response.trim().startsWith('export')) {\n    return response.trim();\n  }\n\n  // Look for export async function anywhere in the response (AI may have added explanation before code)\n  const funcMatch = response.match(/(export\\s+async\\s+function\\s+test\\s*\\([\\s\\S]*)/);\n  if (funcMatch) {\n    return funcMatch[1].trim();\n  }\n\n  // Look for import statement followed by code anywhere in the response\n  const importMatch = response.match(/(import\\s+[\\s\\S]*export\\s+async\\s+function[\\s\\S]*)/);\n  if (importMatch) {\n    return importMatch[1].trim();\n  }\n\n  // Return as-is if we can't extract\n  return response.trim();\n}\n","numLines":764,"startLine":1,"totalLines":764}}}
